  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane townhouses occupy a distinct position in the property market. They sit between standalone houses and apartments, offering more space and privacy than a typical unit while remaining accessible to buyers who have been priced out of detached homes in the same suburb. That positioning creates a broad buyer pool, but it also creates specific expectations around body corporate management, levy costs, and the physical qualities of the property itself. Selling a townhouse well means understanding what that buyer pool values and what it will discount.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying Brisbane townhouses</h2>

      <p>The townhouse buyer pool in Brisbane's inner east is genuinely mixed. Downsizers from larger houses who want to reduce maintenance without moving to an apartment are one significant segment. Young families priced out of standalone homes in the same or nearby suburbs are another. Investors looking for rental yield with manageable body corporate levies make up a third. Each of these groups weighs the body corporate differently, values different aspects of the property, and brings a different level of emotional engagement to the purchase process.</p>

      <p>Downsizers and young families tend to be more emotionally driven buyers, particularly when the property is well-presented and in a tightly held complex. Investors are calculating yield and vacancy risk against competing options. Your agent's approach to marketing should reflect which segment is most likely to produce the strongest result for your specific property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The body corporate factor</h2>

      <p>Most Brisbane townhouses are in community titles schemes, which means the body corporate levies, by-laws, and common property maintenance are all part of what a buyer is purchasing. This is the single factor that most consistently shapes buyer perception and price sensitivity in the townhouse market.</p>

      <p>Low-levy complexes, generally those with quarterly levies under $1,200, attract more owner-occupier buyers and tend to have a larger buyer pool. High-levy complexes push buyers toward a cost-benefit analysis that often favours standalone houses or apartments instead. If your complex has higher-than-average levies, understanding why and being able to explain it clearly matters. Levies that are high because of a well-funded sinking fund and proactive maintenance are received very differently from levies that are high because the complex has persistent maintenance issues.</p>

      <p>The levy amount alone does not tell the whole story, but it is the first number most buyers and their financial advisers look at. Know yours before the first open home.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How townhouses are valued</h2>

      <p>Valuation for Brisbane townhouses is done primarily by comparison with recent sales in the same complex or comparable complexes in the same suburb. The key drivers are land area (or the equivalent outdoor space), aspect and natural light, car accommodation, and internal quality. A two-car tandem garage in an inner-east suburb carries a meaningful premium over a single carport. A north-facing courtyard adds value that a south-facing one of the same size does not.</p>

      <p>Within a complex, recent sales provide the clearest price anchor. If the same floor plan sold six months ago, the market has already established a baseline. Your sale will be compared directly to it, and buyers and their agents will adjust for condition, presentation, and any differences in the specific lot. Knowing what comparable sales within your complex have achieved, and what they looked like at the time of sale, is essential context for setting a price guide.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">End-of-row versus mid-terrace</h2>

      <p>Position within the complex has a measurable effect on price. End-of-row townhouses typically achieve a premium over mid-terrace properties of the same floor plan. The reasons are consistent: more natural light from an additional exposed wall, greater privacy from fewer shared boundaries, and frequently a larger outdoor area or garden. In tightly held inner-east suburbs where outdoor space is at a premium, this difference is meaningful rather than marginal.</p>

      <p>If your townhouse is an end-of-row property, make sure your marketing highlights it clearly. If it is mid-terrace, focus on the internal quality, the outlook, and any particular features of the courtyard or outdoor area that compensate for the positional trade-off.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The body corporate disclosure statement</h2>

      <p>The body corporate disclosure statement is a mandatory document in the sale of any Queensland property in a community titles scheme. For townhouse sales, buyers and their solicitors scrutinise it carefully. The three things buyers look at first are the current levy schedule, the sinking fund balance, and any pending maintenance works or special levies.</p>

      <p>A well-funded sinking fund tells a buyer the complex is being managed responsibly. A depleted sinking fund, or worse, a special levy already raised or pending, signals that a buyer will face additional costs beyond the standard quarterly levies. This directly affects how much they are willing to offer and whether they proceed at all.</p>

      <p>The disclosure statement takes 5 to 10 business days to obtain from the body corporate manager. Order it early, before listing if possible. If the disclosure statement contains anything unfavourable, it is better to know about it when you are pricing the property than when a buyer raises it mid-contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How Brisbane townhouses sell</h2>

      <p>Private treaty is more common than auction for Brisbane townhouses, and the reasons are structural. The townhouse buyer pool, while broad, tends to be more considered and less emotionally competitive than the buyer pool for standalone houses in the same suburb. Buyers comparing multiple townhouses in a suburb are running a systematic cost analysis against their alternatives. That mindset produces less of the auction-day urgency that drives house prices beyond reserve, and more of the deliberate offer-and-counteroffer dynamic that private treaty handles well.</p>

      <p>That said, well-presented townhouses in tightly held inner-east complexes, particularly end-of-row properties with quality renovations, can and do perform strongly at auction when the market is active. The decision between methods depends on the specific property, the current market depth in the suburb, and the composition of buyers in your price range. Your agent should be able to make a clear case for the recommended method based on comparable sales data, not just preference.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to prepare beyond the standard requirements</h2>

      <p>Townhouse sellers need to prepare several things that house sellers do not. The body corporate disclosure statement is the most important and should be ordered at least two weeks before listing to allow time for any queries. Along with the statement, compile the current levy schedule and the most recent body corporate AGM minutes. Buyers and their solicitors will ask for these, and having them ready removes a common friction point in the due diligence process.</p>

      <p>If there are any upcoming maintenance works you are aware of, including roofing, painting, or common area works, be prepared to discuss them. Buyers who discover upcoming works independently tend to view them less favourably than buyers who hear about them from the seller upfront. Transparency in the townhouse market, where body corporate governance is an inherent part of the purchase, builds the buyer's confidence rather than undermining it.</p>

